  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the best small classes for freshmen at Western Carolina University?",
  "response": "Choosing the best small classes for freshmen at Western Carolina University (WCU) depends on your interests, major, and academic goals. However, here are some general recommendations for small, engaging classes that can help you transition smoothly into college life:\n\n### 1. **First-Year Seminar (FYS 140)**\n   - These classes are designed specifically for freshmen and cover a wide range of topics. Class sizes are typically small, and they emphasize critical thinking, writing, and discussion.\n   - Examples: \"The Art of Storytelling,\" \"Exploring Appalachian Culture,\" \"Global Citizenship.\"\n\n### 2. **English Composition (ENGL 101 and 102)**\n   - Smaller sections of these required courses can provide personalized feedback and help you improve your writing skills early in your academic career.\n\n### 3. **Introduction to Psychology (PSY 150)**\n   - Psychology is a popular subject, and smaller sections can offer more interaction with the professor and classmates. It\u2019s a great way to explore human behavior and mental processes.\n\n### 4. **Introduction to Sociology (SOC 110)**\n   - Sociology classes often encourage discussion and critical thinking about society, culture, and social issues. Smaller classes can foster deeper engagement.\n\n### 5. **Public Speaking (COMM 201)**\n   - This class is useful for building confidence and communication skills. Smaller sections allow for more individualized attention and practice.\n\n### 6. **First-Year Experience (FYE) Courses**\n   - These courses are designed to help freshmen acclimate to college life, develop study skills, and explore career options. They are often small and interactive.\n\n### 7. **Creative Writing (ENGL 221)**\n   - If you enjoy writing, this class offers a chance to explore poetry, fiction, or creative nonfiction in a supportive, small-group setting.\n\n### 8. **Introduction to Environmental Science (ENV 150)**\n   - WCU\u2019s location in the Blue Ridge Mountains makes this a great class to explore environmental issues. Smaller sections can include hands-on learning.\n\n### 9. **Art Appreciation or Studio Art (ART 101 or ART 131)**\n   - If you're interested in the arts, these classes offer a chance to explore creativity and art history in a small, hands-on setting.\n\n### 10. **Foreign Language Courses**\n   - Introductory language classes (e.g., Spanish, French, or German) are often small and interactive, providing a great opportunity to learn a new skill.\n\n### Tips for Finding Small Classes:\n- Check the course catalog and look for classes with limited enrollment.\n- Use WCU\u2019s advising resources to find courses that align with your interests and major requirements.\n- Reach out to professors or department advisors for recommendations.\n\nRemember, small classes often provide more opportunities for discussion, individual attention, and community building, which can be especially beneficial during your first year of college.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
